"""
MKT Context Commentary — Haggai chapters 1–2 (all 38 verses)
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-haggai-1-2.py

Haggai is precisely dated — four oracles delivered in 520 BCE, the second
year of Darius I of Persia (522-486 BCE). This makes Haggai the most
precisely dated prophetic book in the OT. The exiles had returned from
Babylon under Sheshbazzar (538 BCE) and Zerubbabel (ca. 537 BCE), but the
temple rebuilding stalled for 18 years. Haggai's task: restart the project.
His key theological argument: agricultural failure is caused by the ruined
temple, not the drought. Rebuild YHWH's house and the blessings will return.
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(layer, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / layer / f'{book}.json'
    return json.loads(p.read_text()) if p.exists() else {}

def save_comm(layer, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / layer / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

HAGGAI = {
  "1": {
    "1": "<p>The precise dating formula — the second year of Darius, the sixth month, the first day — is 29 August 520 BCE by modern reckoning. Darius I (522-486 BCE) was the Persian emperor who consolidated the empire after the chaos following Cambyses' death; his administrative reorganization made provincial rebuilding projects more feasible. The oracle is addressed to Zerubbabel son of Shealtiel (the governor of Judah, of Davidic descent — 1 Chr 3:17-19; the Davidic line is maintained even under Persian governance) and Joshua son of Jehozadak (the high priest — the restoration of the high priestly office after the exile). The combination of civil governor and high priest as co-leaders reflects the post-exilic arrangement that persists through Ezra-Nehemiah.</p>",
    "2": "<p>'Thus says YHWH of hosts: This people says the time has not yet come to rebuild the house of YHWH.' The people's rationalization for not rebuilding is quoted: <em>lo et bo</em> (the time has not yet come). The exact phrase is vague — they do not say the time will never come, only that it has not arrived yet. This is the classic psychology of indefinite deferral: the rebuilding is always a future project, never the present one. YHWH addresses them through Haggai without preamble — the oracle responds directly to the excuse.</p>",
    "3": "<p>'Then the word of YHWH came by the hand of Haggai the prophet.' The formula <em>beyad chaggai hanavi</em> ('by the hand of Haggai the prophet') — the prophet as instrument through whom the divine word travels. This is the standard prophetic commissioning formula, here linking the divine word directly to the historical situation just described. Haggai is identified as <em>hanavi</em> (the prophet) — his prophetic status is clear, though unlike most prophets he is given no genealogy or hometown.</p>",
    "4": "<p>'Is it a time for you yourselves to dwell in your paneled houses, while this house lies in ruins?' The rhetorical contrast: the returnees have rebuilt and paneled their own houses (<em>batim sefunim</em> — houses with cedar paneling, the luxury finish associated with royal architecture, cf. 1 Kgs 7:3, 7) while YHWH's house lies in ruins. The paneled house was not a poverty-house; cedar paneling was expensive and associated with kings. Haggai's charge is not that the people built at all, but that they built luxuriously for themselves while neglecting the divine house.</p>",
    "5": "<p>'Now, therefore, thus says YHWH of hosts: Consider your ways.' <em>Simu levaveichem al darkechem</em> — literally 'set your hearts on your ways.' The imperative recurs four times in the book (1:5, 7; 2:15, 18) as a refrain calling for reflective attention to the agricultural failure surrounding them. Haggai is asking the people to trace the cause-and-effect: their neglect of the temple is the cause of their economic distress. The call to consider is diagnostic, not merely moral — he wants them to reason their way to the connection between their priorities and their plight.</p>",
    "6": "<p>'You have sown much, and harvested little. You eat, but you never have enough; you drink, but you never have your fill. You clothe yourselves, but no one is warm. And he who earns wages does so to put them into a bag with holes.' The covenant-curse catalog of agricultural futility: abundant sowing but sparse harvest (Deut 28:38), eating without satisfaction (Lev 26:26; Deut 28:17), drinking without satisfaction, clothing without warmth, wages that disappear (the bag with holes is a powerful economic metaphor for wage inflation and purchasing-power loss). These are the specific curses of Deuteronomy 28 made visible in the post-exilic economy.</p>",
    "7": "<p>'Thus says YHWH of hosts: Consider your ways.' The second call to consideration (repetition of v. 5) reinforces the diagnostic challenge. Between the two calls, the description of economic failure (v. 6) was given; now the proposed solution follows. The repetition frames the agricultural curse between two imperatives: look at what is happening, understand why it is happening, then act on the understanding.</p>",
    "8": "<p>'Go up to the hills and bring wood and build the house, that I may take pleasure in it and that I may be glorified, says YHWH.' The specific instruction: go to the hill country, cut timber, and build. The reason given is double: YHWH's pleasure (<em>ve'irzeh bo</em>, 'I will be pleased with it') and his glorification (<em>ve'ekavdah</em>, 'I will be glorified'). The temple is not primarily for human benefit but for divine honor — though human benefit follows as consequence. The connection between divine pleasure with the temple and agricultural blessing is made explicit in vv. 9-11.</p>",
    "9": "<p>'You looked for much, and behold, it came to little. And when you brought it home, I blew it away. Why? declares YHWH of hosts. Because of my house that lies in ruins, while each of you busies himself with his own house.' YHWH's intervention in the economy: he 'blew away' (<em>vanafahti vo</em>) what they brought home. The harvest that barely survived the field disappeared at home — YHWH's breath scattered it. The explicit causal statement: 'because of my house that lies in ruins, while each of you busies himself with his own house.' The inversion of priorities has inverted the blessing.</p>",
    "10": "<p>'Therefore the heavens above you have withheld the dew, and the earth has withheld its produce.' Dew (<em>tal</em>) in the Mediterranean climate of Judah was not merely pleasant but agriculturally essential — the summer dew compensated for the lack of rain and kept crops alive between the rainy seasons. YHWH controls the dew (Deut 33:28; Ps 133:3; Prov 3:20; Zech 8:12). The withholding of dew is the covenant curse of Deut 28:24 and Lev 26:19 (sky like iron, earth like bronze).</p>",
    "11": "<p>'And I have called for a drought on the land and the hills, on the grain, the new wine, the oil, on what the ground brings forth, on man and beast, and on all their labors.' The drought (<em>chorev</em>) is a divine decree, not a natural accident — YHWH called for it (<em>qarati chorev</em>). The scope of the drought encompasses all the categories of Israelite agricultural prosperity: grain, wine, oil (the standard triad of covenant blessing — Deut 7:13; 28:51; Hos 2:8; Joel 1:10), plus people, animals, and all labor. The totality of the curse mirrors the totality of the neglect.</p>",
    "12": "<p>'Then Zerubbabel the son of Shealtiel, and Joshua the son of Jehozadak, the high priest, with all the remnant of the people, obeyed the voice of YHWH their God, and the words of Haggai the prophet, as YHWH their God had sent him. And the people feared before YHWH.' The response is immediate and comprehensive: the governor, the high priest, and all the remnant (<em>kol she'erit ha'am</em>) obey and fear. The fear (<em>vayira'u</em>) before YHWH is covenant awe in response to the prophetic word. This is one of the rare instances in the prophetic corpus where the prophet is immediately and wholly obeyed by the entire community — a contrast to the resistance Jeremiah and Isaiah experienced.</p>",
    "13": "<p>'Then Haggai, the messenger of YHWH, spoke to the people with YHWH's message, saying, I am with you, declares YHWH.' Haggai is called <em>malach YHWH</em> (messenger of YHWH) — the same title used of angels. In the context of prophetic literature, it designates him as the authorized bearer of divine speech. The message of reassurance — <em>ani itchem</em>, 'I am with you' — is the divine presence formula of the patriarchal narratives (Gen 26:24; 28:15; 31:3) and the Exodus commission (Exod 3:12). YHWH's presence accompanies the rebuilding from the first day of commitment.</p>",
    "14": "<p>'And YHWH stirred up the spirit of Zerubbabel the son of Shealtiel, governor of Judah, and the spirit of Joshua the son of Jehozadak, the high priest, and the spirit of all the remnant of the people. And they came and worked on the house of YHWH of hosts, their God.' YHWH stirred up (<em>vaya'er YHWH et-ruach</em>) all three groups — the divine initiative precedes and enables the human response. The Spirit-rousing language connects to the Exodus narrative (Exod 35:21 — the Spirit stirring the people to bring offerings for the tabernacle) and to Ezra 1:1 (YHWH stirring the spirit of Cyrus). The actual work begins 23 days after Haggai's first oracle (1:1 is month 6 day 1; v. 15 will mark month 6 day 24).</p>",
    "15": "<p>'On the twenty-fourth day of the month, in the sixth month, in the second year of Darius the king.' The precise date of the work's beginning: 21 September 520 BCE — exactly 23 days after the first oracle. The dating formula closes the first oracle unit and opens the second (2:1 begins the next oracle). The 23-day gap between prophetic call and actual commencement is realistic: organizing a community building project — acquiring timber, assigning labor, clearing the site — would require several weeks of preparation.</p>"
  },
  "2": {
    "1": "<p>'In the seventh month, on the twenty-first day of the month, the word of YHWH came by the hand of Haggai the prophet.' The date is 17 October 520 BCE — the last day of the Feast of Tabernacles (Sukkot), which ran from month 7 day 15 to day 21. This was one of the three great pilgrimage festivals, a time when the entire community was assembled. The choice of Sukkot's closing day for this oracle is significant: Sukkot celebrated both the wilderness wandering (temporary shelters = God's provision during exodus) and the harvest (thanksgiving for the land's produce). A festival about God's presence in a temporary dwelling is the perfect occasion for an oracle about the permanent dwelling being rebuilt.</p>",
    "2": "<p>'Speak now to Zerubbabel the son of Shealtiel, governor of Judah, and to Joshua the son of Jehozadak, the high priest, and to all the remnant of the people, and say.' The same three-part address as 1:1 — Zerubbabel, Joshua, and all the remnant. The civil and religious leadership together with the whole community. This consistent address pattern emphasizes that the restoration project is a community-wide endeavor requiring unified leadership and popular participation.</p>",
    "3": "<p>'Who is left among you who saw this house in its former glory? How do you see it now? Is it not as nothing in your eyes?' The devastating question: those who remembered Solomon's temple (destroyed 586 BCE) and are now watching the modest second temple take shape must make the comparison. Some of the older returnees would indeed have seen the first temple in their youth — Ezra 3:12 records the older men weeping when the foundation of the second temple was laid, while the younger generation shouted for joy. The contrast in scale and beauty was visible and painful. Haggai acknowledges this honestly rather than dismissing it.</p>",
    "4": "<p>'Yet now be strong, O Zerubbabel, declares YHWH. Be strong, O Joshua, son of Jehozadak, the high priest. Be strong, all you people of the land, declares YHWH. Work, for I am with you, declares YHWH of hosts.' The threefold encouragement mirrors the Deuteronomic commissioning formula for Joshua: 'be strong and courageous' (<em>chazaq ve'ematz</em> — Josh 1:6, 7, 9, 18). The same formula that inaugurated the conquest of the land now inaugurates the restoration of the temple. <em>Ani itchem</em> (I am with you) is again the divine-presence guarantee — first given in 1:13, now reiterated as the foundation for work.</p>",
    "5": "<p>'According to the covenant that I made with you when you came out of Egypt. My Spirit remains in your midst. Fear not.' The rebuilding project is grounded in the Sinai covenant and the Exodus — the definitive acts of covenant formation. YHWH's Spirit (<em>ruachi omedet betochechem</em>, 'my Spirit stands/remains in your midst') is the abiding divine presence that accompanied Israel through the wilderness in the cloud and fire (Exod 13:21-22; 14:19-20; Num 11:25). The same Spirit that hovered over the wilderness tabernacle hovers over the post-exilic building site. Fear not: the fear of the community in the face of Persian opposition (Ezra 4) or the disappointing scale of the new temple is answered with the covenant-presence promise.</p>",
    "6": "<p>'For thus says YHWH of hosts: Yet once more, in a little while, I will shake the heavens and the earth and the sea and the dry land.' The eschatological shaking oracle: the cosmic disturbance that will accompany YHWH's ultimate intervention. 'Yet once more' (<em>od achat me'at hi</em>) — one more decisive shaking event, in a brief interval. The heavens, earth, sea, and dry land are the four categories of creation established in Genesis 1. A shaking of all four means a total disruption of the created order. This verse is quoted in Hebrews 12:26-27 to describe the eschatological removal of the created order in favor of the unshakeable kingdom.</p>",
    "7": "<p>'And I will shake all nations, so that the treasures of all nations shall come in, and I will fill this house with glory, says YHWH of hosts.' The shaking of the nations produces the flow of nations' treasures (<em>chemdat kol hagoyim</em>) to the temple. The Hebrew <em>chemdat</em> (singular construct of <em>chemdah</em>, desire/treasure) is the LXX's basis for its plural translation; the Vulgate read it as a singular noun pointing to the Messiah ('the Desired of All Nations'), giving rise to a long Christological interpretation. Most modern scholars prefer the collective reading: the wealth/treasures of all nations flowing to Zion. Either way, the restored temple will be filled with a glory surpassing the first.</p>",
    "8": "<p>'The silver is mine, and the gold is mine, declares YHWH of hosts.' The resources for temple building are YHWH's own — he is not constrained by the community's poverty. This verse answers the practical objection that the post-exilic community cannot fund a temple comparable to Solomon's (who received tribute from the entire ancient Near East). YHWH owns all silver and gold; the human challenge is not a supply problem but an obedience problem.</p>",
    "9": "<p>'The latter glory of this house shall be greater than the former, says YHWH of hosts. And in this place I will give peace, declares YHWH of hosts.' The promise of surpassing glory: the second temple's ultimate glory will exceed Solomon's. This promise was controversial in its immediate fulfillment — the second temple as built by Zerubbabel was plainly less magnificent than Solomon's. The fulfillment was seen in Herod's elaborately rebuilt temple (which was technically still the 'second temple') or, in Christian reading, in the presence of Jesus (John 2:19-21: 'destroy this temple and in three days I will raise it up'). <em>Shalom</em> (peace) — the covenant blessing of YHWH's dwelling in the midst of his people, as in Num 6:24-26.</p>",
    "10": "<p>'On the twenty-fourth day of the ninth month, in the second year of Darius, the word of YHWH came by Haggai the prophet.' The third oracle date: 18 December 520 BCE — three months after work began. The ninth month is the rainy season in Israel, when the agricultural calendar's anxieties about harvest turn to planting hopes. The specific date three months into the project allows Haggai to make a concrete historical observation about the agricultural situation before and after the rebuilding began.</p>",
    "11": "<p>'Thus says YHWH of hosts: Ask the priests about the law.' Haggai engages the priests in a halakhic question — a pedagogical method of using a legal case to establish a theological principle. The priests were the authoritative interpreters of Torah (Deut 17:8-13; Mal 2:7); asking them to rule on a specific case before making the theological application is methodologically precise. The double question that follows is about ritual contagion — the transmission of holiness and impurity — as a framework for the community's spiritual situation.</p>",
    "12": "<p>'If someone carries holy meat in the fold of his garment and touches with his fold bread or stew or wine or oil or any kind of food, does it become holy?' The priests said, No.' The first halakhic case: does holiness transfer by secondary contact? The answer is no — holiness cannot be passed on through a secondary medium (garment carrying holy meat touching another food). This is the standard halakha as understood in Second Temple Judaism: holiness is not contagious in the way impurity is.</p>",
    "13": "<p>'Then Haggai said, If someone who is unclean by contact with a dead body touches any of these, does it become unclean? The priests answered, It does become unclean.' The second case: does impurity transfer through secondary contact? Yes — corpse impurity (<em>tum'at met</em>, the most severe category of ritual impurity in Leviticus 21:1-4; Numbers 19) does transfer through secondary contact. The asymmetry is the key: holiness does not spread outward, but impurity does. Holiness requires proximity to the source; impurity propagates through contact.</p>",
    "14": "<p>'Then Haggai answered and said, So is it with this people, and with this nation before me, declares YHWH, and so with every work of their hands. And what they offer there is unclean.' The application of the halakhic asymmetry: the people's uncleanness (moral/spiritual — their neglect of the covenant, their deferred obedience) has contaminated all their work and all their offerings. The temple that is being rebuilt can transmit holiness only when the community itself is in a state of covenant faithfulness. Unclean hands produce unclean worship, even if the form is technically correct.</p>",
    "15": "<p>'Now then, consider from this day onward. Before stone was placed upon stone in the temple of YHWH, how did you fare?' The fourth call to consideration (cf. 1:5, 7). Haggai asks the people to perform the diagnostic comparison: what was life like before the rebuilding began (before this day, 18 December 520 BCE = three months after work began, but Haggai may be looking back to before day 24 of month 6 = 21 September)? The agricultural record before and after the commitment to build will be the evidence.</p>",
    "16": "<p>'When one came to a heap of twenty measures, there were but ten. When one came to the wine vat to draw fifty measures, there were but twenty.' The quantified experience of covenant-curse-level scarcity: harvests consistently produced half of what they should. Twenty-measure grain heaps yielded ten; fifty-measure wine-vat draws yielded twenty. The shortfalls are not catastrophic but steady — a pattern of consistent underperformance that should have prompted reflection. Haggai's genius is not to announce new punishment but to reframe what the people had already experienced as evidence of their covenant situation.</p>",
    "17": "<p>'I struck you and all the products of your toil with blight and with mildew and with hail, yet you did not turn to me, declares YHWH.' The agricultural interventions: blight (<em>shidafon</em>), mildew (<em>yerayon</em>), and hail (<em>barad</em>) — the three standard Deuteronomic curses (Deut 28:22; Amos 4:9 uses the same pair). The phrase 'yet you did not turn to me' (<em>ve'en etchem elai</em>) is identical to Amos 4:6-11's refrain — YHWH's repeated judgments that produced no repentance. Haggai situates the post-exilic community in the same failure-to-respond pattern as the pre-exilic generation.</p>",
    "18": "<p>'Consider from this day onward, from the twenty-fourth day of the ninth month. Since the day that the foundation of YHWH's temple was laid, consider.' The fifth and final call to consideration — now anchoring to the specific date: the twenty-fourth of the ninth month (18 December 520 BCE), when the oracle is delivered. This date marks the transition point: before this day, the covenant-curse pattern; from this day forward, the covenant-blessing pattern. Haggai is asking the people to observe what happens to the harvest from this turning point onward.</p>",
    "19": "<p>'Is the seed yet in the barn? Indeed, the vine, the fig tree, the pomegranate, and the olive tree have yielded nothing. But from this day on I will bless you.' In December, the seed is in the ground — not yet visible, not yet rewarding the farmer's hope. The fruit trees are bare. But from this day — the day of full commitment to rebuilding, the day of this oracle — YHWH declares the blessing: <em>me'hayom hazeh avareich</em>, 'from this day I will bless.' The blessing is prospective and immediate. The agricultural blessing that had been withheld will now flow — not because the temple is complete, but because the community has turned its heart to YHWH's house.</p>",
    "20": "<p>'The word of YHWH came a second time to Haggai on the twenty-fourth day of the month.' The fourth oracle is delivered on the same day as the third (18 December 520 BCE), but addressed exclusively to Zerubbabel. Two oracles on the same day — the first (vv. 10-19) addressed to the community, the second (vv. 20-23) addressed to the Davidic governor personally. The double oracle on a single day has no other parallel in the prophetic corpus.</p>",
    "21": "<p>'Speak to Zerubbabel, governor of Judah, saying, I am about to shake the heavens and the earth.' The cosmic shaking oracle of v. 6 is now applied personally to Zerubbabel. The connection between the universal shaking and the specific Davidic figure establishes that the shaking of the nations is the context within which YHWH's special favor toward Zerubbabel is exercised. The shaking of creation is not merely cataclysm but the preparation for messianic establishment.</p>",
    "22": "<p>'And I am about to overthrow the throne of kingdoms. I will destroy the strength of the kingdoms of the nations, and overthrow the chariots and their riders. And the horses and their riders shall go down, every one by the sword of his brother.' The military collapse of the nations: thrones overturned, kingdoms destroyed, chariots and horsemen brought down by fratricidal warfare. The 'sword of his brother' recalls the Gideon narrative (Judg 7:22) and the Jehoshaphat narrative (2 Chr 20:23) where YHWH set the enemy nations against each other. The Persian empire will not endure; the kingdoms that oppose YHWH's purposes will destroy each other.</p>",
    "23": "<p>'On that day, declares YHWH of hosts, I will take you, O Zerubbabel my servant, the son of Shealtiel, declares YHWH, and make you like a signet ring, for I have chosen you, declares YHWH of hosts.' The signet ring (<em>chatam</em>) oracle — the reversal of the curse on Jehoiachin. Jeremiah 22:24 had declared that YHWH would tear Jehoiachin (Coniah) from his right hand like a signet ring — the Davidic dynasty was, in effect, de-signetted, its authority revoked. Now YHWH declares Zerubbabel — Jehoiachin's grandson — to be his signet ring: the Davidic authority is re-established, the curse reversed. The Davidic covenant is renewed in Zerubbabel, pointing beyond him to the ultimate Davidic ruler (Matt 1:12 includes both Jehoiachin and Zerubbabel in Jesus's genealogy). Three divine declarations punctuate the verse: 'declares YHWH of hosts,' 'declares YHWH,' 'declares YHWH of hosts' — the triple witness amplifying the irrevocable character of the promise.</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    c = load_comm('mkt-context', 'haggai')
    merge_comm(c, HAGGAI)
    save_comm('mkt-context', 'haggai', c)
    print('haggai mkt-context: merged chapters 1-2')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
